│ tricky one, as it violates the semantics of fast-math flags. │
│ Here's my plan to address it.                                │
│                                                              │
│ ### Analysis and Proposed Fix                                │
│                                                              │
│ The root cause analysis correctly identifies that an         │
│ optimization in `InstCombine` is mis-handling a `select`     │
│ instruction with `nnan` and `nsz` flags. The transformation, │
│ intended to simplify `select(fcmp(x, y), x, y)` patterns     │
│ (min/max), does not preserve these flags, leading to         │
│ incorrect code generation for NaN inputs.                    │
│                                                              │
│ The specific transformation is handled by the                │
│ `canonicalizeFCmpSPF` function. My proposed fix is to        │
│ prevent this function from executing if the `select`         │
│ instruction has any fast-math flags. This is the safest      │
│ approach, as the logic within `canonicalizeFCmpSPF` is not   │
│ designed to correctly propagate or handle these flags.       │
│                                                              │
│ To implement this, I will:                                   │
│ 1.  Modify the signature of `canonicalizeFCmpSPF` to accept  │
│ the `SelectInst` as an argument, so it can check for         │
│ fast-math flags.                                             │
│ 2.  Add a guard at the beginning of `canonicalizeFCmpSPF` to │
│ return early if `SI.hasFastMathFlags()` is true.             │
│ 3.  Update the call site of `canonicalizeFCmpSPF` in         │
│ `visitSelectInst` to pass the `SelectInst` (`SI`).           │
│                                                              │
│ This change will be clean, minimal, and will correctly fix   │
│ the bug by disabling the unsafe optimization.                │
│                                                              │
